(In reply to comment #3)
> What you're asking for sounds like the default behaviour if the job is neither
> a user job nor the a system job.  It will show progress in the status line, 
> and not in a dialog. 
> 
Doh on me; I thought all Jobs had to be "user" or "system"; thanks. 

> Note there are actually two progress regions in the status
> line - one for showing progress on blocking work (for example used by editor
> save), and another for showing progress of jobs.
> 
Right -- the one for Jobs is made visible via calling configurer.setShowProgressIndicator(true) in WorkbenchWindowAdvisor -- how is the other one made visible and active? I've tried things like the method below, but I never actually see anything (even for quite lengthy operations) ... 

/**
 * Get a default ProgressMonitor, using the status-line if possible,
 * accessed via <code>WorkbenchOps.activePage().getActivePart()</code>; 
 * compare also Eclipse-3.0 FAQ # 171.
 * 
 * @return IProgressMonitor
 */
public static IProgressMonitor progressMonitor() {
	final IWorkbenchPart wp = WorkbenchOps.activePage().getActivePart();

	if (wp instanceof IViewPart) {
		final IActionBars bars = ((IViewPart) wp).getViewSite()
					.getActionBars();
		return bars.getStatusLineManager().getProgressMonitor();

	} else if (wp instanceof IEditorPart) {
		final IActionBars bars = ((IEditorPart) wp).getEditorSite()
					.getActionBars();
		return bars.getStatusLineManager().getProgressMonitor();

	} else {
		return new NullProgressMonitor(); 
	}
}

